    title: "A Day in the Life of Gregory Rudeoux",
    topic: "chef life",
    author: "tickle122",
    body:
      "8am: Enter restaurant, turn on equipment, then check the walk-in refrigerator to see what needs to be prepped and to see what we have left over or in excess to determine the day's specials. Also, organize the walk-in in anticipation of that day's deliveries. // 8:30am/9am: Delivery trucks begin to arrive. Check in the delivery and put it away. In between trucks I start doing house prep, i.e. making stocks, butchering fish/meat, preparing soups, etc. // 9:30am: My staff should be here by now. Where is my grill cook? I call them to see what the hold up is. They don't answer. I begin prepping the grill station while simultaneously checking in trucks, putting the delivery away, checking the stock, coming up with and prepping lunch specials and making sure my other cooks are prepping what they need for service. // 10:30am: My grill cook shows up. He had an emergency/car broke down/bus was running late. I finish my morning prep and re-organize/clean the walk-in now that all my trucks have arrived. // 11:00am: We are open for lunch service. I expedite from the window and, if necessary, pass that off to the FOH manager and help the station that is in the weeds get out of the weeds. // 2:00pm: Have the lunch crew clean and prep their stations for the dinner crew while I begin my afternoon prep. This may involve making the creme anglaise for our bread pudding dessert, making another stock (stocks are time intensive), and preparing a prime rib for dinner service. // 3:00pm: The pm sous chef arrives and I discuss with them the day's events, what has been/still needs to be prepped, and what I currently have working. // 3:30pm: Lunch staff transitions to dinner staff. I pull my grill cook aside before he leaves and reprimand him for showing up late. // 4:00pm: I clock out and drink a beer.",
